<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Chapter 2<br>
The battle with the Orc's lasted for many winters. Many of the residents of Everfrost lost their Husbands, Fathers, Mothers, Brothers and Sisters to the evil Redwind and his minions. Homes were burnt to the ground and livestock slaughtered uselessly, leaving many at a complete loss. People were forced to run to the safety of the town of Halas. With so many people crammed into the tight confines of the box canyon of Halas, it wasn't long before the &quot;Plague&quot; set in and ran rampant, like wild fire throughout the city. Young women turned old overnight. Their faces stretched tight over their frail frame as the disease ate away at there flesh from the insides. Strong men turn weak. Bones breaking under the mere weight of standing on their feet.<br>
The city was strong in the medicinal arts and created many potions to counteract this terrible blight, but Barbarians aren't used to being confined within a cities wall for too long. Many families decided to risks losing everything. Home, possessions, family, even their life for the opportunity to be free. <br>
Kesimar being just a baby when Tundra Jack brought him into the Tavern was now almost 6. A seamstress by the name of Kathrine took pity on the boy and provided a home for him. After the terrible events that took his parents, she felt it was the least she could do.<br>
She couldn't help but be amazed at his growth, it seemed as if nothing, even the terrible &quot;Plague&quot; affected the young lad. <br>
Kesimar was strong, agile, and healthy.Truly growing up fast. One particular afternoon Kesimar decided he was going to venture over to the Arena and watch the mock battles and to see if he could get his hands on some Halas Meat Pie. <br>
He studied his surroundings and saw his opportunity to snag a piece of the pie. A vendor wagon was approaching so he used it as cover to get in close to the Market stand. The wagon stopped, Kesimar ducked quickly under the wagon, rolled across until his back was up against the market stand. He could hear the vendor and the stand owner talking about business. He waited until he heard the familiar jingle of the money pouch and he knew it was now or never. He popped up over the side of the sand and he saw his prize. Kesimar quickly shot his hand across the table and snagged what he was after. He was already back down and under the wagon before the owner ever turned around. Kesimar was halfway through eating his last morsel when he could see the man counting his pies and muttering some less then desirable words. Kesimar knew better then to stand there for too long, so he lit out across the courtyard towards the Arena.<br>
The Arena was a very interesting, but brutal place, at times. It wasn't uncommon for someone to lose a finger or maybe even an eye from the ferocity of sparring. This afternoon would be no different.<br>
Kesimar found his usual spot open. There was some large boulders, that spilled over from a mining expedition from years past, that made a nice spot to see everything that went on in the Arena. With his belly full he was ready to see some action. Moments later the announcer told the crowd that they would be having a special treat today. A great homegrown Warrior was going to face off against a Paladin from the nearby city of Qeynos. It was going to be a full contact event. The winner would receive a medallion worth many days wages and then some.<br>
The battle was short. Not even time enough to remember the names of the contestants, the Paladin came out strong. His blade moved swiftly. He caught the Warrior by surprise. Knocked him off balance and brought the hilt of his sword down on the temple of the fallen Warrior. That was the end of it. The Warrior never even staggered. He quietly slumped to the ground, knocked out cold. The crowd was stunned. They had never witnessed such a defeat. Kesimar could hear a pin drop it was so quiet. Soft whispering could be heard throughout the audience. Some asking: &quot;Whats his name? Where did he come from again? and How did he move so fast?&quot; As the crowd settled down from there amazement, the announcer presented the medallion to the Paladin. He graciously accepted and moved out of the Arena for the next round of fights, as if it was no big deal. As the Paladin exited the Arena he walked by Kesimar who was still staring at him in disbelief. The Paladin called out and said: &quot;Boy, whats your name?&quot; in the direction of Kesimar.<br>
Kesimar still caught up in the moment, didn't quite register as to the fact his new hero was talking to him. Kesimar snapped to attention as the Paladin leaned in to Kesimars face and said: &quot; How would you like to make a little money?&quot;<br>
&quot;Run to the counter over there and fetch us some meat pies.&quot; he said as he pointed towards the vendor.<br>
&quot;This isn't good&quot; Kesimar thought to himself. &quot;What if the owner recognizes me.&quot;<br>
The Paladin had pulled a platinum piece out of his pocket and handed it to Kesimar. As he did so he said &quot;Don't worry boy, this will be enough to cover the one you are about to eat as well as the one you already ate. Be on your way lad and hurry, I am famished.&quot;<br>
&quot;How did he know?&quot; Kesimar wondered as he eyed the platinum piece.<br>
The vendor glared at Kesimar evilly as he approached the stand. &quot;What do you want you little thief?&quot; he growled.<br>
Kesimar knew his face was red, but he wasn't about to let the vendor see his guilt. Kesimar produced the platinum coin and calmly said. &quot; Two Halas Meat Pies, Please.&quot;<br>
The vendor was about to reach over and knock Kesimar senseless when he stopped short and backed off in a hurry. Kesimar could see the vendors face go pale as he looked over Kesimars head. Kesimar turned slightly to see what caused such a response. The Paladin had placed his hand on the hilt of his sword as if to say. &quot;One second longer you have Old man before I draw this sword and knock you senseless.&quot;<br>
The vendor pushed the pies forward accepted the coin and went back to his business as if nothing had happened.<br>
The Paladin again leaned into Kesimar and said softly.&quot;If you want to be rich, steal the hearts of men.&quot; There was a twinkle in his eye as he reached into his pouch and produced the medallion he had just won. The Paladin placed it around Kesimars neck and said a final sentence before he would turn and walk away. &quot;Remember boy. Keep you wits sharp and your dagger shaper. Never steal from your friends but take much from your enemies. And always remember to sweet talk the ladies.&quot;<br>
With that the Paladin was gone. Kesimar stood there in awe as he watched this Hero walk down the street.<br>
Many a night would go by with Kesimar falling asleep to those very words that this Paladin said: &quot;Keep your wits sharp and your dagger sharper. Never steal from your friends but take much from your enemies. And always sweet talk the ladies.&quot; Words from a nameless stranger that Kesimar would truly live by. .<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
