<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Chapter 3<br>
The news was spreading quickly that an Army was approaching the wintered lands of Everfrost. Men of all races were coming to rid the land of the Evil hordes of Redwind. The excitement poured out onto the streets quickly as men prepared to join in the fight. Women making food stuff and packing the bags full of ale for the men to eat and drink at the end of the battle. Children scurrying about, desperately to see what all the commotion was about.<br>
It was the first time in years, Kesimar thought to himself, that he actually thought he heard laughter. The town was alive.<br>
The Legions of men that marched down the ramp from Black Burrow was a sight to behold.<br>
Warriors with their armor glistening in the morning sun. Paladins with their cloaks flowing in the slight breeze. Rangers, bows in hand and quivers full. Looking eager to fulfill the dreams of battle. <br>
Wave after wave of men filed down the ramp. Some large, some small, some fat and some thin, but all with that look of hunger for battle in their eyes. <br>
Kesimar couldn't believe what he was seeing. There was actually a small contingent from Erudin of Wizards. Kesimar had only heard stories of them from the occasional jewel vendor. The intellectual powers these Erudite Wizards possessed, some say. could out damage a small army. This was definitely a day that he would remember.<br>
Kesimar new the valleys of Everfrost like the back of his hand, so he ran ahead of the army to get into position so he could see the battle that was about to unfold. As he got near his vantage point high up on the hill side just outside the guard post, Kesimar heard someone he recognized to be his Uncle Bandl.<br>
&quot;Kesimar, Kesimar.&quot; Bandl shouted. &quot;You stay out of sight. Let the army do their job. I don't want you getting hurt.&quot;<br>
Bandl knew that Kesimar had every right to be there and he was actually a little happy that the boy was there to see this mighty force eradicate the very Orcs that took his parents so brutally from him.<br>
&quot;Yes Uncle&quot; Kesimar said quickly, as he ran past.<br>
&quot;Kesimar!&quot; Bandl shouted. &quot;Do you have your dagger?&quot;<br>
The expression on Kesimars face was enough for Bandl to know that Kesimar had his fathers dagger. The boy never let that knife out of his sight.<br>
Bandl couldn't help but remember the time on the dock in Halas he thought he would take Kesimar by surprise by throwing a net over the boy and dumping him in the water. Kesimar produced his dagger and was out of the net and behind him before he could realize what had happened. Kesimar then stuck hi foot behind his leg pushed him off the dock. It was then that he realized the raw potential the boy had.  Faster then any man Bandl could think of. <br>
There were many who witnessed the scene at the docks and on more then one occasion while he was partaking of some Fierce Brew, Bandl heard whispers of Kesimar's name among the Brotherhood of the Rose, a notorious band of Rogues, located in Halas. Bandl knew it wouldn't be long before Kesimar was tempted to use his talents for less then honorable tasks.<br>
But today was a day for Kesimar to see justice metted out at the hands of a mighty army. The lessons learned today could prove to be valuable for a lifetime. <br>
Kesimar could feel the raw power that this mighty army had at their disposal. He couldn't wait to see Redwind running for his life. To see the fear in his eyes would be the least he could ask for. To run his dagger through Redwinds heart would be the ultimate revenge Kesimar could ask for.<br>
Kesimar could feel the blood pumping through his veins. His senses were acute to all that was around him. <br>
Little did Kesimar know but he would find himself having to make a decision regarding Redwind. A decision that would shape his destiny. .<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Chapter 4<br>
Kesimar moved to the top of the hill at the edge of the Tundra to get a better view of the mounting forces that were about to unleash a mighty fury on the evil forces of Redwind.<br>
The amount of Orc's in the river valley was unbelievable. They had taken over all the beautiful temples that were scattered in the hills of Everfrost. <br>
The stench was almost too much to bear. The wind had shifted from the North and was now bringing the foul smell full force into Kesimars face. The carnage that these Orc's called home was more then enough to even upset the most weathered warrior.<br>
The Orc's were well aware of the presence of the large army approaching, but seemed little phased at the impending battle. Their ferocity was world renowned and they counted on that to inspire fear in their enemies. <br>
The first wave of Rangers came to the top of the hill and launched a barrage of arrows into the river valley. The true beauty of of a well orchestrated group of archers was a sight to behold. These Rangers were well trained and extremely fast and impeccably accurate. Arrows would pierce the thick hide of the Orcs and yet they seemed only to annoy the Orc's as they advanced up the hill.<br>
Kesimar didn't realize this was a part of the overall battle plan. The idea was to whip the Orc's into a frenzy so they would charge up the hill without thought to consequences. As they crested the hill the raw power of the Erudites was unleashed. Kesimar could smell the acridity of burnt flesh and the air was alive with electricity. <br>
Kesimar looked down at his arm and saw the hair standing on edge. The goosebumps were raised at the mere thought of what was taking place. The Orc's were literally taken off their feet and hurled backwards from the extreme force of the powerful blasts.<br>
Some of the Orc's definitely had looks of surprise on their face but the determination quickly took over as they continued to advance up the hill.<br>
Kesimar was beginning to doubt what he had been told about Orc's. The were far from mindless creatures. He could see that they had order to their battle. He could see that in the distance that some of the Orc's were breaking off from the central battle forming smaller groups to attack the outer flanks of the advancing army.<br>
Kesimar was so engrossed in the scene before him he didn't notice that someone had crawled up beside him.<br>
&quot;Hey.&quot; a voice said quietly.<br>
Kesimar nearly jumped out of his skin. He looked over to see a young man, about his age, only about 2 feet from him. He was dressed in the traditional Shaman skins and he had that medicinal smell about him of herbs and sweet liquid.<br>
&quot;How goes the battle?&quot; the young man asked. Still in a quiet tone.<br>
Kesimar wasn't much for conversation and was even more annoyed that this Shaman had been able to sneak up on him without even the slightest bit of noise, but Kesimar couldn't help but to admire the Shaman class. After all they did heal his step Mother of the Plague.<br>
&quot;Look.&quot; Kesimar said as he pointed to the band of Orc's that had broken off from the main battle.<br>
&quot;Let's go see where they are going.&quot; the young shaman suggested.<br>
It didn't take the boys long to make there way along the edge of the mountain in the direction of the Orc band. There was a small inlet just east of the Medicine man that Kesimar figured would make a prime point of attack for the Orcs to surprise the army as they went for supplies.<br>
Sure enough the boys got there just ahead of the Orc's. Kesimar couldn't believe his eyes. Redwind was with them. <br>
&quot;Why would he leave the battle to attack supply runs. Kesimar wondered.<br>
No more then the question left his mind when it was answered. Redwind was enlisting the forces of Ox, the Goblins, to come to his aide. They were everywhere. Literally thousands of the green skin horde were dressed in battle mail and ready for death.<br>
Something needed to be done and done quickly. The boys knew that if they were unleashed now the army would be caught in the middle of two forces.<br>
&quot;May the winds of the Wolves carry us fast.&quot; the young Shaman began to chant.<br>
A strange tingling sensation came over Kesimar as his feet lifted only slightly from the ground. The feeling was awesome.<br>
&quot;Run. Warn the others. Go now.&quot; the Shaman yelled as he pointed to the hills.<br>
Kesimar couldn't believe how fast the ground and trees were whipping past him as he ran faster and faster towards the front line. What just took him and the young Shaman an hour to cover, Kesimar literally covered in 10 minutes. He would have to find out what sort of wizardry the Shaman class employed to create such a phenomenon. But he now was not the time, he needed to warn the others of the danger that was behind him.<br>
Kesimar spotted his old friend Tundra Jack and ran toward him.<br>
Jack saw him coming and knew something was wrong.<br>
&quot;Whats up Kes. You look like you saw a Specter?&quot; Jack asked.<br>
Kesimar launched into a barrage of information about what he saw and where they were.<br>
