Kesimar noticed that wildlife abound here in the Western Plains. Lions a plenty.  An occasional wolf could be seen running from the nearby farms, and Kesimar swore he saw the much feared Grizzly as he made his way from the edge of the pine trees.<br>
Needless to say Kesimar picked up the pace towards the Guard Tower. One thing he knew better was not to tangle with the Grizzly. Death would sure follow quickly if one tried to take one on by himself.<br>
The Tower proved to be a good place for Kesimar to take up breakfast. His dried bear meat and fresh muffins he pilfered from the vender in Halas before he left made for a good meal.<br>
&quot;Where you headed son?&quot; the Guard asked as he looked down from his perch.<br>
&quot;High Pass.&quot; Kesomar said knowing full well that this man represented the law and if he ignored him he would make things real tough for him to continue.<br>
&quot;What business do you have there?&quot; the guard asked.<br>
&quot;What is it to you?&quot; Kesimar thought to himself. &quot;Visiting relatives there.&quot; Kesimar said quickly as he put a coy smile on his face.<br>
&quot;Ah well good travels to you then.&quot; the Guard said with a smile on his face.<br>
Kesimar knew that these guys spent many long months out in the towers and family was important to them. They would leave him be at the mere mention of the word family.<br>
Kesimar knew better then to try to extend his rest here for fear that the guard would want to become chatty and ask who he was visiting in High Pass. This guy probably knew everyone there. By the  perverted looks of him probably been with everyone there.<br>
Kesimar wanted to stray from the path but was quickly brought back to his senses when he saw the outline of a Hill Giant looming on the horizon. The river seemed to attract them. Kesimar thought it must be for the easy pillaging of the constant boat merchants who traffic their goods up and down the river.<br>
He heard stories about the wealth some possessed and silently thought to himself there will be a day when I will be able to sneak up to those stupid dorfs and steal them blind without so much as a scratch.<br>
He had a long way to go so he didn't spend much time watching the Giant lumber along the shore. He knew more dangers lie ahead. The roads were pretty well traveled but he knew once he got to the Easter side of the Plains there would be more bandits, packs of wild dogs, and the mythical Griffon laying in wait for the unaware traveler.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
